%N A392409 Square array, A(n,k), n >= 0, k >= 1, read by ascending antidiagonals where A(n,k) is the number of the first 2^n k-almost-primes that are squarefree.
%C A392409 Observe how the array data show A(n,k)/2^n, the density of squarefree k-almost-primes within the k-almost-primes, generally increasing with n. For which k can the relative (asymptotic) density be shown to be 1?
%C A392409 For squarefree primes within the primes the relative density is obviously 1. For k = 2 (squarefree semiprimes within the semiprimes), it is easy to prove. For k = 3 (squarefree 3-almost-primes within the 3-almost-primes), one of the authors (PM) sees a potential route to construct a proof. For k = 4, our calculations show the density within the first 2^27 4-almost-primes already exceeds 6/Pi^2, the asymptotic density of A005117 (squarefree numbers).
%H A392409 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A392409/a392409.txt">Extended table</a> showing 23 full rows and 9 columns (for k-almost-primes not exceeding 2^30), with partial rows up to n=27 and notes.
%H A392409 Charles R Greathouse IV, <a href="https://oeis.org/wiki/Density">Density</a>, OEIS Wiki.
%F A392409 A(n,1) = 2^n.
%F A392409 A(n,k) = 0 iff 2^n < A077622(k).
%e A392409 A(2,2) gives the number of the first 2^2 semiprimes (2-almost-primes) that are squarefree. The first 4 semiprimes are 4, 6, 9, 10, of which 2 are squarefree (6 and 10). So A(2,2) = 2.
